{"action": "edit", "code": "def is_within_boundary(input_grid: np.ndarray, current_point: Tuple[int, int]) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a 2D numpy array and a point, check if the point is within the boundary of the array.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A 2D numpy array\n    current_point: A tuple containing the row and column indices of a point\n    \n    Returns:\n    A boolean value indicating whether the point is within the boundary of the array.\n    \"\"\"\n    rows, cols = input_grid.shape\n    row, col = current_point\n    return 0 <= row < rows and 0 <= col < cols\ndef move_up_two_points(current_point: Tuple[int, int]) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a tuple containing the row and column indices of a point, move the point up two points.\n    \n    Args:\n    current_point: A tuple containing the row and column indices of a point\n    \n    Returns:\n    A tuple containing the row and column indices of the point moved up two points.\n    \"\"\"\n    row, col = current_point\n    return (row - 2, col)\ndef move_down_two_points(current_point: Tuple[int, int]) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a tuple containing the row and column indices of a point, move the point down two points.\n    \n    Args:\n    current_point: A tuple containing the row and column indices of a point\n    \n    Returns:\n    A tuple containing the row and column indices of the point moved down two points.\n    \"\"\"\n    row, col = current_point\n    return (row + 2, col)\ndef find_teal_point(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a 2D numpy array, find the coordinates of the first occurrence of the value \"teal\".\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A 2D numpy array\n    \n    Returns:\n    A tuple containing the row and column indices of the first occurrence of \"teal\" in the input array.\n    \"\"\"\n    teal_point = np.where(input_grid == teal)\n    return (teal_point[0][0], teal_point[1][0])\ndef draw_right_adjacent_points_to_grey